Open notebook in binder:

filoc in Machine Learning¶

filoc is a simple yet powerful and scalable solution to:

  • Prepare hyperparameters
  • Schedule simulations
  • Analyze results

It has the following advantages in comparison to existing solution like neptune:

  • No Server
  • No Database
  • Framework agnostic

The central idea of filoc is to use a file system, local or remote, to handle the data during the entire life-cycle of your machine learning experience, from the definition of the simulation hyperparameters to the post-analysis.

Example¶

Remark: All along this notebook, the star indicates places illustrating the use of to the filoc library.

In this example, you will tune a pytorch model on the IRIS database. We want to perform multiple simulations with various hyperparameters, in order to find the best model and the best training parameters. A reasonable approach is to store the data of each simulation into a separate folders. Maybe something as follows:

Each simulation folder contains three file groups:

hyperparams.jsonSimulation hyperparameters
state.jsonSimulation execution state
epoch_xxx.jsonIntermediate results at the end of epoch xxx

Importing filoc ⭐¶

Most of the time, you only need to import the filoc(...) function. This is the most pythonic way to use filoc:

In [4]:
from filoc import filoc

filoc(...) is a factory function that returns a Filoc object, which is a kind of bi-directional adapter between a DataFrame and files defined in a structured manner.

Creating Filoc instances ⭐¶

You use filoc to read and write all three file groups hyperparams.json, state.json and the result files epoch_xxx.json

So you create three Filoc instances, one for each file group:

In [5]:
hyperparams_loc = filoc('./temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/hyperparameters.json', writable=True)
state_loc       = filoc('./temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/state.json'          , writable=True)
result_loc      = filoc('./temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/epoch_{epoch:d}.json', writable=True)

The filoc(...) first argument defines the path, where you intend to read and write the files. It contains format placeholders, which are part of the data that are read or written.

The writable flag enables the write access to the files. By default the access is read-only.

Now let's prepare the training datasets and the model to train.

Prepare datasets¶

1) Load the IRIS dataset:

In [6]:
iris = sklearn.datasets.load_iris()
print(f'X: {iris.data[0]}, y: {iris.target[0]}')

X: [5.1 3.5 1.4 0.2], y: 0

2) Convert target to one-hot vectors (and by the way convert to pytorch tensor):

In [7]:
all_X = torch.from_numpy(iris.data).type(torch.DoubleTensor)
all_y = torch.from_numpy(keras.utils.to_categorical(iris.target)).type(torch.DoubleTensor) # transform output label to one hot
print(f'all_y:{all_y[0].numpy()}')

all_y:[1. 0. 0.]

3) Shuffle and split dataset into training and validation subsets:

In [8]:
indexes = list(range(len(iris.data))); np.random.shuffle(indexes) # shuffle to randomly draw training and validation sets
train_X = Variable(all_X[indexes[:100]])
train_y = Variable(all_y[indexes[:100]])
valid_X = Variable(all_X[indexes[100:150]])
valid_y = Variable(all_y[indexes[100:150]])

print(f'Shapes: train_X={tuple(train_X.shape)}, valid_X={tuple(valid_X.shape)}, train_y={tuple(train_y.shape)}, valid_y={tuple(valid_y.shape)}')

Shapes: train_X=(100, 4), valid_X=(50, 4), train_y=(100, 3), valid_y=(50, 3)

Preparing the model to train¶

Let's say, you want to train a two-layer feed-forward model with dropout:

In [9]:
class Model(torch.nn.Module):
    """
    Model Input : Flower caracteristics (4 continuous features)
    Model Output: Iris class (3 classes, one-hot vector) 
    """
    def __init__(self, layer1_size, layer2_size, dropout_prob):
        super(Model,self).__init__()
        self.l1      = torch.nn.Linear(4, layer1_size)
        self.l2      = torch.nn.Linear(layer1_size, layer2_size)
        self.l3      = torch.nn.Linear(layer2_size, 3)
        self.dropout = torch.nn.Dropout(p=dropout_prob)
    def forward(self, x):
        sigmoid = torch.nn.Sigmoid()
        relu    = torch.nn.ReLU()
        y       = relu(self.l1(x))
        y       = self.dropout(y)
        y       = relu(self.l2(y))
        y       = self.dropout(y)
        y       = sigmoid(self.l3(y))
        return y

This model has 3 hyperparameters: layer1_size, layer2_size, dropout_prob. We will perform a simple stochastic gradient descent with constant learning rate, so we get a fourth hyperparameter: learning_rate.

So, you get together four hyperparameters to tune:

layer1_size Size of the first hidden layer
layer2_size Size of the second hidden layer
dropout_prob Dropout probability
learning_rateConstant learning rate

Creating the simulation hyperparameter sets¶

To tune the hyperparameters, you will perform a basic grid search.

You first need to define the points of the grid on each dimension:

In [10]:
layer1_sizes   = [9, 27, 81]
layer2_sizes   = [9, 27, 81]
dropout_probs  = [0, 0.25, 0.5]
learning_rates = [0.01, 0.001]

Then you build the cartesian product and pack the result into a DataFrame:

In [11]:
sims_hyperparameters = []
for sim, (layer1_size, layer2_size, dropout_prob, learning_rate) in enumerate(itertools.product(layer1_sizes, layer2_sizes, dropout_probs, learning_rates)):
    sims_hyperparameters.append({
        'sim'           : sim, 
        'layer1_size'   : layer1_size, 
        'layer2_size'   : layer1_size, 
        'dropout_prob'  : dropout_prob, 
        'learning_rate' : learning_rate
    })
sims_hyperparameters = pd.DataFrame(sims_hyperparameters)

Saving the simulation hyperparameter sets ⭐¶

Now you will use filoc to save each simulation hyperparameters set to its dedicated file...

It is actually a piece of cake:

In [12]:
hyperparams_loc.write_contents(sims_hyperparameters)

Filoc.write_contents(...) created all the 54 hyperparameters files at once! It substituted the sim variable defined in the filoc path ./temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/hyperparameters.json by the sim value defined in the sim_hyperparameters list, then created the files and filled them with the remaining variables of the object.

Preparing the state file ⭐¶

During a simulation campaign you need to manage the simulation execution state in order to:

  • Concurrently execute simulations(concurrent safe)
  • Be resilient in case of problems
  • Monitor the progress of your simulation campaign

In this example, you will work with four states:

state description
init simulation is ready to be executed
running simulation is currently executed
failed simulation has failed and stopped
succeeded simulation has ended properly

With filoc, it is a piece of cake to initialize the state files:

In [15]:
sim_states = sims_hyperparameters[['sim']].copy()
sim_states['state'] = 'init'

with state_loc.lock():
    state_loc.write_contents(sim_states)

Here, the `write_contents(...)` call has been packed into a state_loc.lock() with-block. It ensures that no other processes currently read from nor write to the state files.

The locking implementation is relative simple and works only against other locks (calls within state_loc.lock()).

Preparing the simulation script ⭐¶

In this example, we pack the training into a single function, which will be executed by multiple execution threads concurrently. (Usually, you would write a dedicated python script and execute it in a separated process).

In [16]:
def train_and_validate(sim):
    # Load hyperparameters
    
    # with open(f'./temp/iris/sim={sim}/hyperparameters.json') as f: hyps = DataFrame(json.loads(f))  #  (code without filoc)
    hyps = hyperparams_loc.read_content(sim = sim)                                                    #  (code with filoc)

    model    = Model(hyps.layer1_size, hyps.layer2_size, hyps.dropout_prob).double()
    loss_fun = torch.nn.BCELoss(reduction='mean')
    opt      = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=hyps.learning_rate)

    for epoch in range(10000 + 1):  # +1 to save last result
        # train
        train_y_pred = model(train_X)
        train_loss   = loss_fun(train_y_pred, train_y)    
        train_acc    = (torch.argmax(train_y_pred, dim=1) == torch.argmax(train_y, dim=1)).sum().item() / len(train_y)
        opt.zero_grad()
        train_loss.backward() # back prop
        opt.step()

        # validate and save results (every 100 epoch)
        if epoch % 100 == 0:
            with torch.no_grad():
                valid_y_pred = model(valid_X)
                valid_loss   = loss_fun(valid_y_pred, valid_y)    
                valid_acc    = (torch.argmax(valid_y_pred, dim=1) == torch.argmax(valid_y, dim=1)).sum().item() / len(valid_y)

                result = {
                    'sim'        : sim,
                    'epoch'      : epoch,
                    'train_loss' : train_loss.item(),
                    'train_acc'  : train_acc,
                    'valid_loss' : valid_loss.item(),
                    'valid_acc'  : valid_acc,
                }

                # Save epoch result 
                
                # with open(f'./temp/iris/sim={sim}/epoch_{epoch}.json', 'w') as f: json.dumps(result, f)  #  (code without filoc)
                result_loc.write_content(result)                                                           #  (code with filoc)

It is a standard training loop:

  • The simulation consists of 10000 + 1 epochs
  • For each epoch, the neural network is trained on the training set (forward + backward propagation + gradient descent)
  • Every 100 epochs, we export intermediate results:
    • The loss and the accuracy on both the training and validation sets

Here, filoc is used at two places:

  • read_content(...) reads the simulation hyperparameters at the beginning
  • write_content(...) writes the epoch result every 100 epochs

If you don't want to reference filoc in your training script, just replace the read_content(...) and write_content(...) as described in the previous code.

Prepare parallelization ⭐¶

To parallelize the training, we need a small piece of code, that books the next simulation to execute. This piece of code must be concurrent safe, as it will be executed in multiple threads, processes or machines:

In [17]:
def book_next_simulation():
    with state_loc.lock():                              # 
        sim_states_all  = state_loc.read_contents()     # 
        if len(sim_states_all) == 0: 
            return None  # No sim to execute
        
        sim_states_init = sim_states_all.query("state == 'init'")
        if len(sim_states_init) == 0: 
            return None  # No sim to execute
        
        sim_state = sim_states_init.iloc[0, :].copy()
        sim_state.state = 'running'
        state_loc.write_content(sim_state)             # 
        return sim_state.sim  # returns the sim id

The use of state_loc.lock() ensures that only one thread at a time can book a simulation.

You finally need a loop to process the simulations:

In [18]:
def process_simulations(executor_name):
    try:
        while True:
            sim = book_next_simulation()
            if sim is None:
                print(f'{executor_name}: no simulation to process')
                return
            print(f'{executor_name}: processing simulation {sim}')
            try:
                train_and_validate(sim)
                state_loc.write_content({'sim': sim, 'state': 'succeeded'})
            except:
                state_loc.write_content({'sim': sim, 'state': 'failed'})
                
            print(f'{executor_name}: processed  simulation {sim}')
    except:
        traceback.print_exc()

And now we can start a few executors, that will concurrently execute the simulations:

In [19]:
with ThreadPoolExecutor() as executor:
    executor.submit(process_simulations, "executor1")
    executor.submit(process_simulations, "executor2")
    executor.submit(process_simulations, "executor3")
    executor.submit(process_simulations, "executor4")

Monitoring executions ⭐¶

During the execution, you can use filoc to monitor the execution state. In practice we would do that in another notebook.

Here is how it works:

In [20]:
from filoc import filoc
mon_state_loc = filoc('./temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/state.json', timestamp_col='modified')

`timestamp_col='modified'` adds the file timestamp to a column named `modified`

Analyzing results ⭐¶

filoc allows us to seamlessly analyze the simulations, namely during and after the execution. Look how it works. We first create a new Filoc that joins all file contents together:

In [23]:
analysis_loc = filoc({
  'hyp'    : './temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/hyperparameters.json',
  'state'  : './temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/state.json',
  'result' : './temp/iris/sim={sim:d}/epoch_{epoch:d}.json',    
}, cache_locpath='temp/cache/iris/cache.bin')

`cache_locpath` is used to improve the processing in the case of a great amount of files to process, especially if the files are store on a remote file system

By feeding `filoc(...)` with a dictionary, we build a composite `Filoc`, which is able to work with multiple files groups.

If you think of each data group as building a SQL table (where each file contains key-values which defines the values of a single row), then filoc performs a join operation on all tables. The join keys are the placeholders found in the paths. Let's see the result:

In [24]:
df = analysis_loc.read_contents()

You get a denormalized [fact table](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fact_table) with the complete simulation data (the result of the 54 simulations)!! Now you can slice and dice this pandas DataFrame to analyze the result!

The column names are prefixed with the the key provided in the definition dictionary. The variables sim and index are prefixed by "index.", because they are join variables, used to join all tables together.

So let's start the analysis: get a first insight on the results by plotting the evolution of the "validation accuracy" for all simulations:

In [25]:
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [15, 8]
ax = plt.gca()
df.groupby(by='index.sim').plot(x='index.epoch', y='result.train_acc', ax=ax, legend=None);

We clearly see that some simulation reach the a very high prediction accurary, some slowly, some very fast. Other simulations stuck at a quite low accuracy level.

Now let's see the influence of every single hyperparameter on the "validation accuracy" at final epoch (the 10000th epoch):

In [26]:
df_epoch = df[df['index.epoch'] == 10000]

hyps = ['hyp.layer1_size', 'hyp.layer2_size', 'hyp.dropout_prob', 'hyp.learning_rate']
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,5), dpi= 80)
for idx, hyp in enumerate(hyps):
    fig.add_subplot(1, len(hyps), idx+1)
    sns.boxplot  (x=hyp, y="result.valid_acc", data=df_epoch, whis=np.inf)   # plots the statistical percentile box
    sns.stripplot(x=hyp, y="result.valid_acc", data=df_epoch, color=".3")    # plots the simulations as dot

We let you analyze the results yourself and implement additional visualizations. In practice, we are able now to identify good hyperparameters, that produce good prediction models and that are fast to train. But we could also consider to re-fine the hyperparameter search to other ranges.

In this notebook, we primarly wanted to illustrate how you can use filoc to your machine learning trainings! So it's up to your to clone this notebook and try yourself!!

Conclusion¶

You have seen how filoc can be used to help to manage the whole life-cycle machine learning, by:

  • Preparing simulation hyperparameters and folders
  • Executing concurrently multiple simulations and monitoring them
  • Analyze the simulation results
